    "summary": "Greek Theater of the Classical Era (c. 496–406 BC) produced the dramatic tradition that is the direct ancestor of Western theater — with tragedies by Aeschylus, Sophocles, and Euripides, and comedies by Aristophanes, performed at religious festivals in Athens before audiences of thousands and exploring questions of fate, justice, politics, and human nature that remain compelling today.\n\nAthenian drama developed from choral performances at festivals of Dionysus, evolving through Aeschylus's innovation of a second actor (enabling genuine dialogue), Sophocles's introduction of a third actor and painted scenery, and Euripides's psychologically realistic characters. The three great tragedians — Aeschylus (Oresteia, Prometheus Bound), Sophocles (Oedipus Rex, Antigone), and Euripides (Medea, The Bacchae) — together created a dramatic tradition of unmatched depth. Performances took place in the Theater of Dionysus on the slope of the Acropolis; male actors wore masks and elevated shoes; the plays were staged as competitive festivals. Aristophanes's comedies (The Clouds, The Wasps, The Birds) used humor to mock politicians, philosophers, and social trends, making [[event:1024|Socrates' Trial and Execution]]'s Socrates a comic villain. The theater's influence on Western literature, from Shakespeare to opera to modern film, is incalculable.",
